# Game Technical Constraints

## Engine: Kaplay

All games use **Kaplay** (the maintained fork of Kaboom.js). It is bundled locally — no CDN needed.

```html
<script src="../_lib/kaplay.js"></script>
<script>
kaplay({ width: 800, height: 500, background: [2, 6, 23], crisp: true });
</script>
```

- `kaplay()` auto-creates and appends a `<canvas>` to `<body>`.
- All Kaplay functions (`add`, `onUpdate`, `onKeyPress`, `dt`, `vec2`, `rgb`, `go`, `scene`, etc.) are global after init.
- Do NOT use npm packages, do NOT use ES module imports. One `<script>` tag is all you need.
- Kaplay docs: https://kaplayjs.com/docs/api

## Viewport

- The game world must fit entirely within one fixed-size canvas.
- No scrolling cameras, no infinite maps, no multi-screen levels.
- Typical sizes: 800x500 (landscape) or 440x440 (square). Pick what fits the game.

## Sprites & assets

- Use Kaplay's built-in primitives: `rect()`, `circle()`, `text()` for shapes and labels.
- Use Unicode emojis for quick sprites: `text("🚀", { size: 32 })`.
- Do NOT load external image URLs (CORS and broken-link risk).

## Controls

- Default to **WASD + Arrow keys** for movement via `onKeyDown()` / `onKeyPress()`.
- Always include a restart mechanism (Space or Enter after game over, using `go("game")` to restart the scene).

## Game structure

- Every game must have: a score counter, a win/lose condition, and a restart path.
- Use `scene("game", () => { ... })` and `go("game")` for clean restarts.
- Use `onUpdate(() => { ... })` for game logic and `onDraw(() => { ... })` for custom rendering.
- Use `dt()` for frame-rate-independent movement.
